instance life_cycle_stages : DTDFVocab:EvolutionStage [
    base:desc "1) Enrichment of the BIM model with device‑level metadata (sensors, actuators, controllers) by Building Control Engineers, establishing a unified semantic foundation. 2) Model‑Driven Engineering (MDE) transformations extract structured representations (e.g., IFC extensions or domain ontologies) from the enriched BIM, automatically mapping BIM constructs to runtime components. 3) Artifacts (executable services, APIs, database schemas) are generated and deployed from the transformed models with minimal manual configuration, enabling rapid iteration. 4) Runtime operation continuously synchronises sensor data and actuator commands via real‑time data exchange protocols, providing real‑time state alignment between the physical building and its Digital Twin. 5) Continuous evolution is supported by modular extension points, allowing new analytics or control logic to be plugged in without modifying core artifacts. Governance is realised through defined stakeholder roles—Building Control Engineer, Facility Manager, DT Engineer—each responsible for specific lifecycle stages."
]

instance fidelity_and_validity_considerations : DTDFVocab:FidelityConsideration [
    base:desc "Model fidelity is ensured by embedding the semantic constraints of the BIM model into Ditto’s policy framework, which enforces value ranges and units during runtime message validation. Verification of actuator command safety is performed by the policy engine before dispatch, preventing unsafe state transitions. Data validity is maintained via Hono’s reliable message broker guaranteeing at‑least‑once delivery and Ditto’s persistent event store, providing recoverable event streams. Fault tolerance is achieved by persistent storage in Ditto, so that events are not lost during service interruptions. No formal static verification of control logic is described; the system relies on runtime validation and memory of past events to ensure consistent behavior."
]

